description:
src/lib.rs:566-581 acquires std::sync::Mutex guard ('let _g = ENV_LOCK.lock().unwrap()') and holds it across 'store.put(...).await' on line 579. clippy::await_holding_lock flags this with the warning 'consider using an async-aware Mutex type or ensuring the MutexGuard is dropped before calling await'.

Why it matters: std::sync::Mutex blocks the OS thread, not the async task. Holding it across await means another tokio task running on the same thread (under the multi_thread runtime, or on the same single thread under current_thread) cannot make progress. Today the test does not deadlock because put() returns InvalidUri before any real await yield point — but a future change to put() that introduces an actual async operation (any HTTP call) before the InvalidUri check would cause this test to deadlock with itself or other ENV_LOCK-using tests.

Two correct fixes (NOT mutually exclusive):
  (1) Drop the guard before .await:
      let store = {
          let _g = ENV_LOCK.lock().unwrap();
          unsafe { std::env::set_var("GCP_ACCESS_TOKEN", "dummy-token") };
          let store = GcpSmBackend::from_uri(...).unwrap();
          unsafe { std::env::remove_var("GCP_ACCESS_TOKEN") };
          store
      };
      let result = store.put(...).await;
  (2) Replace ENV_LOCK with tokio::sync::Mutex (which is async-aware and safe to hold across .await).

(1) is preferable because env var manipulation does not need to span the await — by the time put() runs, the token has already been read into self.access_token.

Engineering basis: this is a real footgun, not stylistic preference. The test is currently safe by accident, not by design.
